\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textsf{Do knots have `friends'? ATLAS may provide answers}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Waders such as red knots 
\emph on
Calidris canutus
\emph default
 are highly social, and gather in large non-breeding flocks in the Wadden
 Sea, where they feed on the macrozoobenthos buried in intertidal mudflats.
 Knots have been shown to use social information in lab settings,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bijleveld et al.
 2015.

\emph on
 Behav.
 Processes
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and are hypothesised to use communal roosts as information centres.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bijleveld et al.
 2010.

\emph on
 Oikos
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Persistent association with specific individuals could help knots make use
 of collective sensing, or exploit an informed flockmate.
 We used high frequency
\emph on
 (1 minute interval) 
\emph default
ATLAS
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Time of Arrival radio tracking using 4.2 g tags glued to dorsal surface;
 5-point median filter applied.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 tracking data to test whether knots have non-random associations â€” in a
 sense, do knots have `friends'?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textsf{Knot association is low, but 10
\backslash
% of pairs are `friends'}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found that of 556 unique knot pairs tracked over 44 tidal intervals 
\emph on
(high tide to high tide, ~19 days)
\emph default
, ~10% were associated 
\emph on
(proportion of positions in proximity, Kolmogorov-Smirnov test)
\emph default
 higher than expected by chance.
 10% were associated less than expected.
\end_layout

