\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textsf{Association is largely environmentally driven}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within tidal intervals, knot association was highest in the hours just before
 
\emph on
(advancing tide)
\emph default
 and after 
\emph on
(receding tide)
\emph default
 high tide, and lowest around low tide (Fig.
 1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
textsf{Conclusion 
\backslash
& future work}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our results align with the idea that wader flocks are good examples of random
 mixing driven by environmental effects.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Myers 1983.
 
\emph on
Behav.
 Ecol.
 Sociobiol.
\emph default
; Conklin & Colwell 2007.
 
\emph on
JOFO.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, red knots have been shown to have consistent individual differences
 in exploratory behaviour, which may be linked to different foraging needs
 and movement patterns.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bijleveld et al.
 2014.
 
\emph on
Proc.
 Royal Soc.
 B.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It remains to be tested whether knot personality is a factor in determining
 association in the dynamic Wadden Sea landscape.
